{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Use British English|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox UK legislation |short_title = Newspaper Libel and Registration Act 1881 |parliament = Parliament of the United Kingdom |long_title = An Act to amend the Law of Newspaper Libel, and to provide for the Registration of Newspaper Proprietors. |year = 1881 |statute_book_chapter = 44 & 45 Vict. c.60 |introduced_by = [[Private Member's Bill]] |territorial_extent = England, Wales and (later Northern) Ireland |royal_assent = 27 August 1881 |commencement = |repeal_date = |amendments = {{Unbulleted list|[[Law of Libel Amendment Act 1888]]|[[Administration of Justice (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1933]]|[[Criminal Law Act 1977]]|[[Deregulation Act 2015]]}} |related_legislation = |repealing_legislation= |status = Amended |original_text = http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Vict/44-45/60/enacted |legislation_history = |use_new_UK-LEG = yes |revised_text = }}
The '''Newspaper Libel and Registration Act 1881''' (44 & 45 Vict. c.60) was an act passed by the Parliament of the United Kingdom. Introduced as a [[Private Member's Bill]], it reduced the legislative burden on newspaper proprietors with regard to the offence of [[libel]]; as a ''quid pro quo'', the compulsory registration of proprietors (abolished by the [[Newspapers, Printers, and Reading Rooms Repeal Act 1869]]) was reintroduced.<ref name="O'MalleySoley2000">{{cite book|author1=Tom O'Malley|author2=Clive Soley|title=Regulating The Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r47jvyaECDoC&pg=PA47|accessdate=13 April 2012|date=20 November 2000|publisher=Pluto Press|isbn=978-0-7453-1197-5|page=47}}</ref>
Following the removal of compulsory registration in 1869, newspaper owners had begun to look to anonymity as a protection against lawsuits arising out of the publication of libellous statements.<ref name="O'MalleySoley2000"/> At the same time, the judgment in ''[[Purcell v Sowler]]'' (1877) saw a newspaper proprietor successfully sued despite recognition that the libellous statements his newspaper had published were merely quoted verbatim from the testimony of a member of the public made at public meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/ldjudgmt/jd991028/rey02.htm|title=Judgment -House of Lords - Reynolds v. Times Newspapers Limited and Others|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=13 April 2012|author=Lord Nicholas of Birkenhead|date=28 October 1999}}</ref> Against this backdrop, two successive [[select committee]]s were established to look at the law of libel; the first made no report, but the second took on the evidence of the first, and made several recommendations. In the words of [[John Dyson Hutchinson|John Hutchinson]], MP for [[Halifax (UK Parliament constituency)|Halifax]], "the Bill embodied the recommendations of [the second] Committee, and was confined to them exclusively".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1881/may/11/newspapers-law-of-libel-bill#S3V0261P0_18810511_HOC_21|publisher=Hansard|accessdate=13 April 2012|title=Newspapers (law of libel) bill}}</ref> The bill itself took the form of a [[Private Member's Bill]].<ref name="O'MalleySoley2000"/>
In terms of content, section 2 of the Act (as it became when it received royal assent on 27 August 1881<ref name="legislation"/>) introduced a new defence for newspaper proprietors in cases where the libel stemmed from a fair, accurate and non-malicious report of a publicly held meeting.<ref name="O'MalleySoley2000"/> This extension of [[qualified privilege]] was then "amplified" by the [[Law of Libel Amendment Act 1888]],<ref>{{cite journal|volume=26|journal=California Law Review|page=239 |year=1938|title=Preserving Liberty of the Press by the Defense of Privilege in Libel Actions|author=John M. Hall}}</ref> which in doing so repealed section 2 of the 1881 Act. Repealed at the same time was section 3 ("No prosecution for newspaper libel without fiat of Attorney General").<ref name="legislation">{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Vict/44-45/60|title=Newspaper Libel and Registration Act 1881|publisher=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref> The Act also benefited newspaper owners insofar as it instituted provisions (section 4, 5 and 6) for the quicker (and hence cheaper) resolution of newspaper libel cases.<ref name="O'MalleySoley2000"/> Contrary to expectations, however, the passage of the Act correlated with an increase, rather than decrease, in the number of [[defamatory libel]] (criminal) actions being brought against newspapers. Whether the two were causally linked is not known, however.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lawreform.ie/_fileupload/consultation%20papers/cpCrimeofLibel.htm|title=Consultation paper on the crime of libel|publisher=The Law Reform Commission|location=Ireland|date=August 1991|accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref>
In return, proprietors were happy to accept the reintroduction of compulsory registration that had been removed in 1869 (now provided for by sections 7 to 15 of the 1881 Act inclusive).<ref name="O'MalleySoley2000"/> These registration clauses, which included an exemption for proprietors who are already registered companies, were not repealed until 2015<ref name="legislation"/> and were still enforced.<ref name="companieshouse"/> For the purposes of the Act, a newspaper is defined as "any paper containing public news, intelligence, or occurrences, or any remarks or observations therein printed for sale, and published ... periodically, or in parts or numbers at intervals not exceeding 26 days".<ref name="companieshouse">{{cite web|url=http://www.companieshouse.gov.uk/about//pdf/gpo3.pdf|date=May 2011|publisher=Companies House|title=Newspaper Libel and Registration Act 1881|accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref> As of 2009, 56 newspapers and their proprietors were centrally registered as a result of these provisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inforrm.files.wordpress.com/2011/09/list-of-newspaper-registrations.doc|title=Newspapers Database - List|publisher=Companies House|year=2010|accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref> Under section 19 of the Act, it never applied to Scotland.<ref name="legislation"/>
The provisions on registration in sections 7 to 18 were repealed by the [[Deregulation Act 2015]] as being no longer of practical use.<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2015/20/schedule/23 Deregulation Act 2015, Schedule 23.]</ref> As a result, only section 4 remains in force, and that only in relation to Northern Ireland and courts hearing charges there of [[blasphemous libel]].
