{{Refimprove|date=November 2015}}

In the [[comic book]] publishing industry, a '''one-shot''' is a comic book published as a single, standalone issue, with a self-contained story, and not as part of an ongoing series or [[miniseries (comics)|miniseries]].<ref>Albert, Aaron. [http://comicbooks.about.com/od/glossary/g/One-Shot-Definition.htm "One Shot Definition"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118194924/http://comicbooks.about.com/od/glossary/g/One-Shot-Definition.htm |date=2012-11-18 }}. [[About Entertainment]]. Retrieved July 8, 2016.</ref> In the television industry, one-shots sometimes serve as a [[television pilot|pilot]] to field interest in a new series.{{fact|date=July 2016}}

==Japan==
In the [[Japan]]ese [[manga]] industry, the concept of one-shot is expressed by the term {{nihongo|''yomikiri''|読み切り}}, which implies that the comic is presented in its entirety without any continuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anime.stackexchange.com/questions/8390/what-is-the-purpose-of-one-shot-manga|title=What is the purpose of one-shot manga?|website=anime.stackexchange.com}}</ref> One-shot manga are often written for contests, and sometimes later developed into a full-length manga series (much like a [[television pilot]]). Many popular manga series began as one-shot stories, including ''[[Dragon Ball (manga)|Dragon Ball]]'', ''[[Fist of the North Star]]'', ''[[Naruto]]'', ''[[Bleach (manga)|Bleach]]'', ''[[One Piece]]'', ''[[Berserk (manga)|Berserk]]'', ''[[Kinnikuman]]'' and ''[[Death Note]]'', among others. Some noted manga authors, such as [[Akira Toriyama]] and [[Rumiko Takahashi]], have worked on numerous one-shot stories in addition to their serialized works. ''[[Rising Stars of Manga]]'' was an annual competition for [[original English-language manga|original English-language]] one-shot manga, many of which have gone on to become full-length manga series.

==United States==
In the [[United States]], one-shots are usually labeled with a "#1" despite there being no following issues, and are sometimes [[subtitle (titling)|subtitled]] as "specials".  On occasion, a character or concept will appear in a series of one-shots, in cases where the subject matter is not financially lucrative enough to merit an [[ongoing series|ongoing]] or [[Limited series (comics)|limited series]], but still popular enough to be published on a regular basis, often annually or quarterly. A current example of a series of one-shots would be [[Marvel Comics]]' ''[[Franklin Richards: Son of a Genius]]'' publications. This type of one-shot is not to be confused with a [[Annual publication#Comic books|comic book annual]], which is typically a companion publication to an established ongoing series.{{fact|date=July 2016}}

==Other countries==
The term has also been borrowed into the [[Franco-Belgian comics]] industry, with basically the same meaning, although there, it mostly refers to [[comic album|albums]].{{fact|date=July 2016}}

