{{Infobox person | name = Ross John Edgley | image = Ross Edgley (31843832508) (cropped).jpg | alt = | caption = Edgley in 2018. | birthname = | death_date = | death_place = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|10|13}} | birth_place = [[Grantham]], England | othername = | occupation = Adventurer | yearsactive = | spouse = | domesticpartner = | website = https://rossedgley.com/ }}
'''Ross John Edgley''' (born 13 October 1985) is a Sunday Times Bestselling Author and Adventurer based in [[Cheshire]], [[England]]. Edgley holds multiple world records including the world's longest staged sea swim.
In November 2018, he became the first person to swim around [[Great Britain]] without stepping on land. His journey was documented as a weekly internet series, ''"Ross Edgley's Great British Swim"'', produced by [[Red Bull]]. Edgley also set a new world record 74 days into his challenge, for the longest staged sea swim, according to the [[Open water swimming|World Open Water Swimming Association]].<ref>{{cite news |date=4 November 2018 |title=Ross Edgley sets record for round Great Britain swim |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46088884 |work=BBC |access-date=4 November 2018 }}</ref> About the new records, he said, "It's my hope that people remember the Great British Swim as an example or experiment in both mental and physical fortitude."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/11/04/europe/ross-edgley-swims-around-great-britain-trnd/index.html|title=After 5 months at sea, Ross Edgley completes swim around Great Britain|last=CNN|first=Amanda Jackson,|work=CNN|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>
==Personal life== [[File:Ross_Edgley_at_Margate.jpg|thumb|left|Ross Edgley completed the [[Great British Swim]] at Margate, November 4 2018.]] Born into a sporting family, his father was a [[tennis]] coach while his mother was a sprinter. Edgley began his sports career at the age of fourteen as a swimmer and practicing water polo where he played in the British men's water polo championship and also for his [[Great Britain men's national water polo team|national team]]. After his competitive career, Edgley took part in the reality show ''Tough Guy or Chicken''? of the [[BBC]]. Edgley graduated in sports science from [[Loughborough University]] and wrote editorial columns as a fitness expert for magazines like [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]], ''[[Men's Health]]'', ''[[GQ]]'', ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', ''[[Men's Fitness]]'' and others. More recently he has directed and presented the program on [[Sky UK]] ''Welcome to the Fight Club''. He also took part in a 26-mile (42 km) charity marathon on the Silverstone circuit, pulling a [[Cooper Countryman]] with a weight of 1,400 kg in a time of 19 hours, 36 minutes and 43 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Larbi |first=Miranda |date=23 March 2017 |title=Meet Ross Edgley: the real life Action Man who runs with trees tied to his back |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/03/23/meet-ross-edgley-the-real-life-action-man-who-runs-with-trees-tied-to-his-back-6516769/?ito=cbshare |work=Metro |location= |access-date=4 November 2018 }}</ref> In May of 2018, he released his first book titled "The Worlds Fittest Book" detailing his advice and experience on fitness and health that helped him on his own athletic feats. Other athletic accomplishments Ross has achieved include climbing a rope the length of Everest<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/worlds-strongest-rope-climb-ross-edgley|title=What I learnt from climbing a rope repeatedly until I’d scaled the height of Everest|last=Edgley|first=Ross|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref>, and completing a triathlon with a 100Lb tree on his back.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/train-for-triathlon|title=How I trained to run a triathlon while carrying a tree|last=Edgley|first=Ross|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref>
