{{Refimprove|date=May 2008}}
'''Set-jetting''' is the trend of traveling to destinations that are first seen in movies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cosypursuits.com/2017/06/17/set-jetting-location-vacations-book-tourism-detective-travel/|title=Set Jetting, Location Vacations, Book Tourism & Detective Travel|date=2017-06-17|website=Cosy Pursuits|access-date=2017-07-01}}</ref>  It is also referred to as a "Location Vacation". Touring [[London]] in a high-speed boat like [[James Bond]], or visiting the stately homes that are seen in the [[Jane Austen in popular culture|Jane Austen films]] are good examples. 

The term was first coined in the US press in the ''[[New York Post]]'' by journalist [[Gretchen Kelly]].<ref name="kelly">{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/set_jetting_2IA9GEMZ2VSWSoDH5qdZ9M|title=Set Jetting|author=Gretchen Kelly|publisher=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=2009-11-05 | date=2008-02-19}}</ref> An analysis about the use of Geospatial technologies in setjetting was proposed by [[Thierry Joliveau]] in [[The Cartographic Journal]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Connecting Real and Imaginary Places through Geospatial Technologies: Examples from Set-jetting and Art-oriented Tourism|url = http://www.maneyonline.com/doi/abs/10.1179/000870409X415570|journal = The Cartographic Journal|date = 2009-02-01|issn = 0008-7041|pages = 36–45|volume = 46|issue = 1|doi = 10.1179/000870409X415570|first = Thierry|last = Joliveau}}</ref>

Corporations, convention and tourism boards are exploiting the trend, creating their own set-jetting travel maps, like the ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]'' movie map published by VisitBritain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitbritain.us/campaigns/film/index.aspx?url=/movies|title=Movie Map|work=visitbritain.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617071016/http://www.visitbritain.us/campaigns/film/index.aspx?url=%2Fmovies|archivedate=17 June 2008|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090205150218/http://www.visitbritain.us/Images/Golden%20Age%20Map%20FINAL_tcm20-114120.pdf Elizabeth the Golden Age]. ''visitBritain.com/thegoldenage''</ref>

